# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heat
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:heat/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:heat/advection] In the fields of physics, engineering, and earth sciences, **advection** is the transport of a substance or quantity by bulk motion of a fluid.
[src:heat/advection] The properties of that substance are carried with it.
[src:heat/advection] Generally the majority of the advected substance is also a fluid.
[src:heat/advection] The properties that are carried with the advected substance are conserved properties such as energy.
[src:heat/advection] An example of advection is the transport of pollutants or silt in a river by bulk water flow downstream.
[src:heat/advection] Another commonly advected quantity is energy or enthalpy.
[src:heat/advection] Here the fluid may be any material that contains thermal energy, such as water or air.
[src:heat/advection] In general, any substance or conserved extensive quantity can be advected by a fluid that can hold or contain the quantity or substance.
[src:heat/advection] During advection, a fluid transports some conserved quantity or material via bulk motion.
[src:heat/advection] The fluid's motion is described mathematically as a vector field, and the transported material is described by a scalar field showing its distribution over space.
[src:heat/advection] Advection requires currents in the fluid, and so cannot happen in rigid solids.
[src:heat/advection] It does not include transport of substances by molecular diffusion.
[src:heat/advection] Advection is sometimes confused with the more encompassing process of convection, which is the combination of advective transport and diffusive transport.
[src:heat/advection] In meteorology it is the transfer by the wind of an atmospheric mass.
[src:heat/advection] Advection is important for the formation of orographic clouds and the precipitation of water from clouds, as part of the hydrological cycle.
[src:heat/advection] The **advection equation** is a first-order hyperbolic partial differential equation that governs the motion of a conserved scalar field as it is advected by a known velocity vector field.
[src:heat/advection] It is derived using the scalar field's conservation law, together with Gauss's theorem, and taking the infinitesimal limit.
[src:heat/advection] One easily visualized example of advection is the transport of ink dumped into a river.
[src:heat/advection] As the river flows, ink will move downstream in a "pulse" via advection, as the water's movement itself transports the ink.
[src:heat/advection] If added to a lake without significant bulk water flow, the ink would simply disperse outwards from its source in a diffusive manner, which is not advection.
[src:heat/advection] Note that as it moves downstream, the "pulse" of ink will also spread via diffusion.
[src:heat/advection] The sum of these processes is called convection.
[src:heat/advection] In particular, if the flow is steady, then ${\mathbf {u} }\cdot \nabla \psi =0,$ which shows that $\psi$ is constant (because ${\textstyle \nabla \psi =0}$ for any vector ${\textstyle \mathbf {u} }$ ) along a streamline.
[src:heat/advection] Here, $\mathbf {a}$ is a vector field instead of the scalar field $\psi$ .
[src:heat/advection] Solutions to the advection equation can be approximated using numerical methods, where interest typically centers on discontinuous "shock" solutions and necessary conditions for convergence (e.g. the CFL condition).
[src:heat/advection] Since skew symmetry implies only imaginary eigenvalues, this form reduces the "blow up" and "spectral blocking" often experienced in numerical solutions with sharp discontinuities.
[src:heat/advection] The term *advection* often serves as a synonym for *convection*, and this correspondence of terms is used in the literature.
[src:heat/advection] More technically, convection applies to the movement of a fluid (often due to density gradients created by thermal gradients), whereas advection is the movement of some material by the velocity of the fluid.
[src:heat/advection] Thus, although it might seem confusing, it is technically correct to think of momentum being advected by the velocity field in the Navier-Stokes equations, although the resulting motion would be considered to be convection.
[src:heat/advection] Because of the specific use of the term convection to indicate transport in association with thermal gradients, it is probably safer to use the term advection if one is uncertain about which terminology best describes their particular system.
[src:heat/advection] In meteorology and physical oceanography, advection often refers to the horizontal transport of some property of the atmosphere or ocean, such as heat, humidity or salinity, and convection generally refers to vertical transport (vertical advection).
[src:heat/advection] Advection is important for the formation of orographic clouds (terrain-forced convection) and the precipitation of water from clouds, as part of the hydrological cycle.
[src:heat/advection] The advection equation also applies if the quantity being advected is represented by a probability density function at each point, although accounting for diffusion is more difficult.
[src:heat/air-pump] An **air pump** is a pump for pushing air.
[src:heat/air-pump] Examples include a bicycle pump, pumps that are used to aerate an aquarium or a pond via an airstone; a gas compressor used to power a pneumatic tool, air horn or pipe organ; a bellows used to encourage a fire; a vacuum cleaner and a vacuum pump.
[src:heat/air-pump] All air pumps contain a part that moves (vane, piston, impeller, diaphragm etc.) which drives the flow of air.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the air gets moved, an area of low pressure gets created which fills up with more air.
[src:heat/air-pump] Pumps and compressors use very similar mechanisms, and basically perform the same action, but in different fluid regimes.
[src:heat/air-pump] In 1649, German scientist and inventor Otto von Guericke invented the spool vacuum air pump.
[src:heat/air-pump] Guericke's vacuum pump decreased any potential leaks between the piston and the cylinder by utilizing washers made from leather.
[src:heat/air-pump] In Britain, the first effective vacuum pump for scientific purposes was constructed in 1658 by English polymath Robert Hooke, on behalf of Anglo-Irish natural philosopher Robert Boyle.
[src:heat/air-pump] Boyle used the term "air pump" (among others) for his own vacuum pump as well as Guericke's, and they have often been referred to as such ever since.
[src:heat/air-pump] In 1705, English scientist Francis Hauksbee, developed a style of a double-barrelled air pump.
[src:heat/air-pump] Hauksbee's double-barrelled air pump was used primarily for scientific research, and had the ability to create a vacuum.
[src:heat/air-pump] The invention of the air pump led to the invention of the vacuum pump and the vacuum tube.
[src:heat/air-pump] The vacuum tube lead to a revelation in many different areas.
[src:heat/air-pump] An air compressor turns power (gasoline or an electrical motor) into potential energy.
[src:heat/air-pump] This potential energy is stored in a tank and forces air into the tank creating positive pressure.
[src:heat/air-pump] Normally a hose is connected to the tank and then when opened with a valve or switch air is shot out of the hose at high speeds.
[src:heat/air-pump] A simple mechanism that consists of a flexible bag that has rigid boards or handles on each side.
[src:heat/air-pump] The bag can be expanded and contracted by working the handles away from each other and together forcing air out of the nozzle.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the bag is inflated or the handles are pulled away from each other a valve is opened on the side allowing air in.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the handles are pushed together that valve is closed and air is forced out the end.
[src:heat/air-pump] Through the use of a piston in a cylinder this pump creates pressure by using a one way valve and a piston that is controlled by the handle.
[src:heat/air-pump] The Bicycle pump is a vertical hand pump that is used to inflate bicycle tires. these pumps are very common and can be used to inflate many things with the use of an adapter.
[src:heat/air-pump] In the case of air pumps, diaphragm pumps are considered to be a type of pump that utilizes positive displacement.
[src:heat/air-pump] A simple diaphragm pump contains a chamber that acts like a springy diaphragm.
[src:heat/air-pump] When compressed, the air within the diaphragm gets expelled.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the diaphragm is decompressed, the chamber refills with air.
[src:heat/air-pump] A simple example for a diaphragm pump is a foot pump that requires the user to constantly step up and down on the pump to inflate something.
[src:heat/air-pump] Several companies developed engine-driven tire pumps in the brass era of the automobile.
[src:heat/air-pump] A simple reciprocating pump is commonly made up of a cylinder with an inlet, an outlet, and a piston within.
[src:heat/air-pump] The inlet and the outlet are used to direct the flow of air, while the piston is used to generate the flow of air.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the piston is pulled up, air gets sucked into the pump through the inlet.
[src:heat/air-pump] The pump chamber depressurizes as it fills with air.
[src:heat/air-pump] When the piston is forced down, the air becomes compressed and closes the inlet.
[src:heat/air-pump] A rotary pump uses gears that mesh together to capture and pressurize air through movement of the gears.
[src:heat/air-pump] This allows a high pressure when discharged.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] "**An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction**" is a scientific paper by Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford, which was published in the Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society in 1798.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] The paper provided a substantial challenge to established theories of heat, and began the 19th century revolution in thermodynamics.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was an opponent of the caloric theory of heat which held that heat is a fluid that could be neither created nor destroyed.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He had further developed the view that all gases and liquids are absolute non-conductors of heat.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] His views were out of step with the accepted science of the time and the latter theory had particularly been attacked by John Dalton and John Leslie.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was heavily influenced by the argument from design and it is likely that he wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Though Rumford was to come to associate heat with motion, there is no evidence that he was committed to the kinetic theory or the principle of *vis viva*.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] In his 1798 paper, Rumford acknowledged that he had predecessors in the notion that heat was a form of motion.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Those predecessors included Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke, John Locke, and Henry Cavendish.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring out cannon barrels at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] At that time, cannons were cast at the foundry with an extra section of metal forward of what would become the muzzle, and this section was removed and discarded later in the manufacturing process.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford took an unfinished cannon and modified this section to allow it to be enclosed by a watertight box while a blunted boring tool was used on it.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He showed that water in this box could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours, and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining were the same.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford also argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He contended that the only thing communicated to the barrel was motion.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford made no attempt to further quantify the heat generated or to measure the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Most established scientists, such as William Henry, as well as Thomas Thomson, believed that there was enough uncertainty in the caloric theory to allow its adaptation to account for the new results.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] It had certainly proved robust and adaptable up to that time.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Furthermore, Thomson, Jöns Jakob Berzelius, and Antoine César Becquerel observed that electricity could be indefinitely generated by friction.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] No educated scientist of the time was willing to hold that electricity was not a fluid.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Ultimately, Rumford's claim of the "inexhaustible" supply of heat was a reckless extrapolation from the study.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Charles Haldat made some penetrating criticisms of the reproducibility of Rumford's results and it is possible to see the whole experiment as somewhat tendentious.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] However, the experiment inspired the work of James Prescott Joule in the 1840s.
[src:heat/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Joule's more exact measurements were pivotal in establishing the kinetic theory at the expense of caloric.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] The journal is the successor to *Journal der Physik*, published from 1790 until 1794, and **Neues Journal der Physik**, published from 1795 until 1797.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] The journal has been published under a variety of names (**Annalen der Physik**, **Annalen der Physik und der physikalischen Chemie**, **Annalen der Physik und Chemie**, *Wiedemann's Annalen der Physik und Chemie*) during its history.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] Originally, *Annalen der Physik* was published in German, then a leading scientific language.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] From the 1950s to the 1980s, the journal published in both German and English.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] Initially, only foreign authors contributed articles in English but from the 1970s German-speaking authors increasingly wrote in English in order to reach an international audience.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] After the German reunification in 1990, English became the only language of the journal.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] The importance of *Annalen der Physik* unquestionably peaked in 1905 with Albert Einstein's Annus Mirabilis papers.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] In the 1920s, the journal lost ground to the concurrent *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] With the 1933 emigration wave, German-language journals lost many of their best authors.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] During Nazi Germany, it was considered to represent "the more conservative elements within the German physics community", alongside *Physikalische Zeitschrift*.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] Between 1944 and 1946 publication ceased due to World War II.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] Granted permission to restart by Soviet military authorities in August 1946, the journal subsequently maintained a policy until 1992 of co-editorship by one person from East Germany and one from West Germany.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] After German reunification, the journal was acquired by Wiley-VCH.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] A relaunch of the journal with new editor and new contents was announced for 2012.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] As a result of the 2012 relaunch, *Annalen der Physik* changed scope and updated the membership of the editorial board.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] With each editor, the numbering of volumes restarted from 1 (co-existent with a continuous numbering, a perpetual source of confusion).
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] The journal was often referred to by the editor's name: *Gilberts Annalen*, *Poggendorfs Annalen*, *Wiedemanns Annalen* and so on, or for short *Pogg.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] After Drude, the work was divided between two editors: experimentalists Wilhelm Wien (1907–1928) and Eduard Grüneisen (1929–1949) and theoretician Max Planck (1907–1943, who had been associate editor from 1895).
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] In these times, peer-review was not yet standard.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] Einstein, for example, just sent his manuscripts to Planck, who then published them.
[src:heat/annalen-der-physik] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2024 impact factor of 2.5.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] It is generally accepted that Lavoisier's great accomplishments in chemistry stem largely from his changing the science from a qualitative to a quantitative one.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier is noted for his discovery of the role oxygen plays in combustion, opposing the prior phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He named oxygen (1778), recognizing it as an element, and also recognized hydrogen as an element (1783).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier helped construct the metric system, wrote the first extensive list of elements, in which he predicted the existence of silicon, and helped to reform chemical nomenclature.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His wife and laboratory assistant, Marie-Anne Paulze Lavoisier, became a renowned chemist in her own right, and worked with him to develop the metric system of measurements.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was a powerful member of a number of aristocratic councils, and an administrator of the *Ferme générale*.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The *Ferme générale* was one of the most hated components of the *Ancien Régime* because of the profits it took at the expense of the state, the secrecy of the terms of its contracts, and the violence of its armed agents.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] All of these political and economic activities enabled him to fund his scientific research.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] At the height of the French Revolution, he was charged with tax fraud and selling adulterated tobacco, and was guillotined despite appeals to spare his life in recognition of his contributions to science.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] A year and a half later, he was exonerated by the French government.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Antoine-Laurent Lavoisier was born to a wealthy family of the nobility in Paris on 26 August 1743.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The son of an attorney at the Parlement of Paris, he inherited a large fortune at the age of five upon the death of his mother.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier began his schooling at the Collège des Quatre-Nations, University of Paris (also known as the Collège Mazarin) in Paris in 1754 at the age of 11.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In his last two years (1760–1761) at the school, his scientific interests were aroused, and he studied chemistry, botany, astronomy, and mathematics.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the philosophy class he came under the tutelage of Abbé Nicolas Louis de Lacaille, a distinguished mathematician and observational astronomer who imbued the young Lavoisier with an interest in meteorological observation, an enthusiasm which never left him.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier entered the school of law, where he received a bachelor's degree in 1763 and a licentiate in 1764.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier received a law degree and was admitted to the bar, but never practiced as a lawyer.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] However, he continued his scientific education in his spare time.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's education was filled with the ideals of the French Enlightenment of the time, and he was fascinated by Pierre Macquer's dictionary of chemistry.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He attended lectures in the natural sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's devotion and passion for chemistry were largely influenced by Étienne Condillac, a prominent French scholar of the 18th century.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His first chemical publication appeared in 1764.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] From 1763 to 1767, he studied geology under Jean-Étienne Guettard.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In collaboration with Guettard, Lavoisier worked on a geological survey of Alsace–Lorraine in June 1767.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1764 he read his first paper to the French Academy of Sciences, France's most elite scientific society, on the chemical and physical properties of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulfate), and in 1766 he was awarded a gold medal by the King for an essay on the problems of urban street lighting.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1768 Lavoisier received a provisional appointment to the Academy of Sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1769, he worked on the first geological map of France.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] While Lavoisier is commonly known for his contributions to the sciences, he also dedicated a significant portion of his fortune and work toward benefitting the public.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was a humanitarian—he cared deeply about the people in his country and often concerned himself with improving the livelihood of the population by agriculture, industry, and the sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The first instance of this occurred in 1765, when he submitted an essay on improving urban street lighting to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Three years later in 1768, he focused on a new project to design an aqueduct.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The goal was to bring water from the river Yvette into Paris so that the citizens could have clean drinking water.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] But, since the construction never commenced, he instead turned his focus to purifying the water from the Seine.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This was the project that interested Lavoisier in the chemistry of water and public sanitation duties.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Additionally, he was interested in air quality and spent some time studying the health risks associated with gunpowder's effect on the air.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1772, he performed a study on how to reconstruct the Hôtel-Dieu hospital, after it had been damaged by fire, in a way that would allow proper ventilation and clean air throughout.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] At the time, the prisons in Paris were known to be largely unlivable and the prisoners' treatment inhumane.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier took part in investigations in 1780 (and again in 1791) on the hygiene in prisons and had made suggestions to improve living conditions, suggestions which were largely ignored.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Once a part of the academy, Lavoisier also held his own competitions to push the direction of research towards bettering the public and his own work.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier had a vision of public education having roots in "scientific sociability" and philanthropy.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier gained a vast majority of his income through buying stock in the General Farm, which allowed him to work on science full-time, live comfortably, and allowed him to contribute financially to better the community.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He also pushed for public education in the sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He founded two organizations, Lycée and Musée des Arts et Métiers, which were created to serve as educational tools for the public.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Funded by the wealthy and noble, the Lycée regularly taught courses to the public beginning in 1793.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] At the age of 26, around the time he was elected to the Academy of Sciences, Lavoisier bought a share in the *Ferme générale*, a tax farming financial company which advanced the estimated tax revenue to the royal government in return for the right to collect the taxes.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] On behalf of the Ferme générale Lavoisier commissioned the building of a wall around Paris so that customs duties could be collected from those transporting goods into and out of the city.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His participation in the collection of its taxes did not help his reputation when the Reign of Terror began in France, as taxes and poor government reform were the primary motivators during the French Revolution.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier consolidated his social and economic position when, in 1771 at age 28, he married Marie-Anne Pierrette Paulze, the 13-year-old daughter of a senior member of the *Ferme générale*.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] She was to play an important part in Lavoisier's scientific career—notably, she translated English documents for him, including Richard Kirwan's *Essay on Phlogiston* and Joseph Priestley's research.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In addition, she assisted him in the laboratory and created many sketches and carved engravings of the laboratory instruments used by Lavoisier and his colleagues for their scientific works.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Madame Lavoisier edited and published Antoine's memoirs (whether any English translations of those memoirs have survived is unknown as of today) and hosted parties at which eminent scientists discussed ideas and problems related to chemistry.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] A portrait of Antoine and Marie-Anne Lavoisier was painted by the famed artist Jacques-Louis David.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Completed in 1788 on the eve of the Revolution, the painting was denied a customary public display at the Paris Salon for fear that it might inflame anti-aristocratic passions.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] For three years following his entry into the *Ferme générale*, Lavoisier's scientific activity diminished somewhat, for much of his time was taken up with official *Ferme générale* business.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He did, however, present one important memoir to the Academy of Sciences during this period, on the supposed conversion of water into earth by evaporation.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He also attempted to introduce reforms in the French monetary and taxation system to help the peasants.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The Farmers General held a monopoly of the production, import and sale of tobacco in France, and the taxes they levied on tobacco brought revenues of 30 million livres a year.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This revenue began to fall because of a growing black market in tobacco that was smuggled and adulterated, most commonly with ash and water.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also noticed that the addition of a small amount of ash improved the flavour of tobacco.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Of one vendor selling adulterated goods, he wrote "His tobacco enjoys a very good reputation in the province... the very small proportion of ash that is added gives it a particularly pungent flavour that consumers look for.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Perhaps the Farm could gain some advantage by adding a bit of this liquid mixture when the tobacco is fabricated." Lavoisier also found that while adding a lot of water to bulk the tobacco up would cause it to ferment and smell bad, the addition of a very small amount improved the product.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Thereafter the factories of the Farmers General added, as he recommended, a consistent 6.3% of water by volume to the tobacco they processed.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] To allow for this addition, the Farmers General delivered to retailers seventeen ounces of tobacco while only charging for sixteen.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] To ensure that only these authorised amounts were added, and to exclude the black market, Lavoisier saw to it that a watertight system of checks, accounts, supervision and testing made it very difficult for retailers to source contraband tobacco or to improve their profits by bulking it up.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He was energetic and rigorous in implementing this, and the systems he introduced were deeply unpopular with the tobacco retailers across the country.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This unpopularity was to have consequences for him during the French Revolution.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier urged the establishment of a Royal Commission on Agriculture.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He then served as its Secretary and spent considerable sums of his own money in order to improve the agricultural yields in the Sologne, an area where farmland was of poor quality.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The humidity of the region often led to a blight of the rye harvest, causing outbreaks of ergotism among the population.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1788 Lavoisier presented a report to the Commission detailing ten years of efforts on his experimental farm to introduce new crops and types of livestock.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His conclusion was that despite the possibilities of agricultural reforms, the tax system left tenant farmers with so little that it was unrealistic to expect them to change their traditional practices.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's researches on combustion were carried out in the midst of a very busy schedule of public and private duties, especially in connection with the *Ferme Générale*.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] There were also innumerable reports for and committees of the Academy of Sciences to investigate specific problems on order of the royal government.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier, whose organizing skills were outstanding, frequently landed the task of writing up such official reports.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1775 he was made one of four commissioners of gunpowder appointed to replace a private company, similar to the Ferme Générale, which had proved unsatisfactory in supplying France with its munitions requirements.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] As a result of his efforts, both the quantity and quality of French gunpowder greatly improved, and it became a source of revenue for the government.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His appointment to the Gunpowder Commission brought one great benefit to Lavoisier's scientific career as well.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] As a commissioner, he enjoyed both a house and a laboratory in the Royal Arsenal.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Here he lived and worked between 1775 and 1792.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In June 1791, Lavoisier made a loan of 71,000 livres to Pierre Samuel du Pont de Nemours to buy a printing works so that du Pont could publish a newspaper, *La Correspondance Patriotique*.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The plan was for this to include both reports of debates in the National Constituent Assembly as well as papers from the Academy of Sciences.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The revolution quickly disrupted the elder du Pont's first newspaper, but his son E.I. du Pont soon launched *Le Republicain* and published Lavoisier's latest chemistry texts.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also chaired the commission set up to establish a uniform system of weights and measures which in March 1791 recommended the adoption of the metric system.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The new system of weights and measures was adopted by the Convention on 1 August 1793.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was one of the 27 Farmers General who, by order of the convention, were all to be detained.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Although temporarily going into hiding, on 30 November 1793 he handed himself into the Port Royal convent for questioning.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He claimed he had not operated on this commission for many years, having instead devoted himself to science.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier himself was removed from the commission on weights and measures on 23 December 1793, together with mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace and several other members, for political reasons.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] One of his last major works was a proposal to the National Convention for the reform of French education.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He also intervened on behalf of a number of foreign-born scientists including mathematician Joseph Louis Lagrange, helping to exempt them from a mandate stripping all foreigners of possessions and freedom.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] As the French Revolution gained momentum, attacks mounted on the deeply unpopular *Ferme générale*, and it was eventually abolished in March 1791.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1792 Lavoisier was forced to resign from his post on the Gunpowder Commission and to move from his house and laboratory at the Royal Arsenal.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] On 8 August 1793, all the learned societies, including the Academy of Sciences, were suppressed at the request of Abbé Grégoire.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] On 24 November 1793, the arrest of all the former tax farmers was ordered.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier and the other Farmers General faced nine accusations of defrauding the state of money owed to it, and of adding water to tobacco before selling it.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier drafted their defense, refuting the financial accusations, reminding the court of how they had maintained a consistently high quality of tobacco.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The court, however, was inclined to believe that by condemning them and seizing the goods of the Farmers General, it would recover huge sums for the state.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was convicted and guillotined on 8 May 1794 in Paris, at the age of 50, along with his 27 co-defendants.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] A year and a half after his execution, Lavoisier was completely exonerated by the French government.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] During the White Terror, his belongings were delivered to his widow.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] A brief note was included, reading "To the widow of Lavoisier, who was falsely convicted".
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] An apocryphal story exists regarding Lavoisier's execution in which the scientist blinked his eyes to demonstrate that the head retained some consciousness after being severed.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Some variants of the story include Joseph-Louis Lagrange as being the scientist to observe and record Lavoisier's blinking.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This story was not recorded in contemporary accounts of Lavoisier's death, and the execution site was too removed from the public for Lagrange to have viewed Lavoisier's alleged experiment.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The story likely originated in a 1990s Discovery Channel documentary about guillotines and then subsequently spread online, becoming what one source describes as an urban legend.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Contrary to prevailing thought at the time, Lavoisier theorized that common air, or one of its components, combines with substances when they are burned.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He demonstrated this through experiment.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] During late 1772 Lavoisier turned his attention to the phenomenon of combustion, the topic on which he was to make his most significant contribution to science.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He reported the results of his first experiments on combustion in a note to the Academy on 20 October, in which he reported that when phosphorus burned, it combined with a large quantity of air to produce acid spirit of phosphorus, and that the phosphorus increased in weight on burning.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] During 1773 Lavoisier determined to review thoroughly the literature on air, particularly "fixed air," and to repeat many of the experiments of other workers in the field.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He published an account of this review in 1774 in a book entitled *Opuscules physiques et chimiques* (Physical and Chemical Essays).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the course of this review, he made his first full study of the work of Joseph Black, the Scottish chemist who had carried out a series of classic quantitative experiments on the mild and caustic alkalies.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier recognized that Black's fixed air was identical with the air evolved when metal calces were reduced with charcoal and even suggested that the air which combined with metals on calcination and increased the weight might be Black's fixed air, that is, CO2.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the spring of 1774, Lavoisier carried out experiments on the calcination of tin and lead in sealed vessels, the results of which conclusively confirmed that the increase in weight of metals in combustion was due to combination with air.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] But the question remained about whether it was in combination with common atmospheric air or with only a part of atmospheric air.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In October the English chemist Joseph Priestley visited Paris, where he met Lavoisier and told him of the air which he had produced by heating the red calx of mercury with a burning glass and which had supported combustion with extreme vigor.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Priestley at this time was unsure of the nature of this gas, but he felt that it was an especially pure form of common air.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier carried out his own research on this peculiar substance.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The result was his memoir *On the Nature of the Principle Which Combines with Metals during Their Calcination and Increases Their Weight*, read to the Academy on 26 April 1775 (commonly referred to as the Easter Memoir).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the original memoir, Lavoisier showed that the mercury calx was a true metallic calx in that it could be reduced with charcoal, giving off Black's fixed air in the process.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] When reduced without charcoal, it gave off an air which supported respiration and combustion in an enhanced way.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He concluded that this was just a pure form of common air and that it was the air itself "undivided, without alteration, without decomposition" which combined with metals on calcination.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] After returning from Paris, Priestley took up once again his investigation of the air from mercury calx.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His results now showed that this air was not just an especially pure form of common air but was "five or six times better than common air, for the purpose of respiration, inflammation, and ... every other use of common air".
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He called the air dephlogisticated air, as he thought it was common air deprived of its phlogiston.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Since it was therefore in a state to absorb a much greater quantity of phlogiston given off by burning bodies and respiring animals, the greatly enhanced combustion of substances and the greater ease of breathing in this air were explained.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's researches included some of the first truly quantitative chemical experiments.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He carefully weighed the reactants and products of a chemical reaction in a sealed glass vessel so that no gases could escape, which was a crucial step in the advancement of chemistry.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1774, he showed that, although matter can change its state in a chemical reaction, the total mass of matter is the same at the end as at the beginning of every chemical change.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Thus, for instance, if a piece of wood is burned to ashes, the total mass remains unchanged if gaseous reactants and products are included.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's experiments supported the law of conservation of mass.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier, together with Louis-Bernard Guyton de Morveau, Claude-Louis Berthollet, and Antoine François de Fourcroy, submitted a new program for the reforms of chemical nomenclature to the academy in 1787, for there was virtually no rational system of chemical nomenclature at this time.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This work, titled *Méthode de nomenclature chimique* (*Method of Chemical Nomenclature*, 1787), introduced a new system which was tied inextricably to Lavoisier's new oxygen theory of chemistry.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The classical elements of earth, air, fire, and water were discarded, and instead some 33 substances which could not be decomposed into simpler substances by any known chemical means were provisionally listed as elements.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Similarly, salts of the "ic" acids were given the terminal letters "ate," as in copper sulfate, whereas the salts of the "ous" acids terminated with the suffix "ite," as in copper sulfite.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The total effect of the new nomenclature can be gauged by comparing the new name "copper sulfate" with the old term "vitriol of Venus." Lavoisier's new nomenclature spread throughout Europe and to the United States and became common use in the field of chemistry.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This marked the beginning of the anti-phlogistic approach to the field.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier is commonly cited as a central contributor to the chemical revolution.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His precise measurements and meticulous keeping of balance sheets throughout his experiment were vital to the widespread acceptance of the law of conservation of mass.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His introduction of new terminology, a binomial system modeled after that of Linnaeus, also helps to mark the dramatic changes in the field which are referred to generally as the chemical revolution.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier encountered much opposition in trying to change the field, especially from British phlogistic scientists.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Joseph Priestley, Richard Kirwan, James Keir, and William Nicholson, among others, argued that quantification of substances did not imply conservation of mass.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Rather than reporting factual evidence, opposition claimed Lavoisier was misinterpreting the implications of his research.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] One of Lavoisier's allies, Jean Baptiste Biot, wrote of Lavoisier's methodology, "one felt the necessity of linking accuracy in experiments to rigor of reasoning." His opposition argued that precision in experimentation did not imply precision in inferences and reasoning.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Despite opposition, Lavoisier continued to use precise instrumentation to convince other chemists of his conclusions, often results to five to eight decimal places.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The "official" version of Lavoisier's Easter Memoir appeared in 1778.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the intervening period, Lavoisier had ample time to repeat some of Priestley's latest experiments and perform some new ones of his own.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In addition to studying Priestley's dephlogisticated air, he studied more thoroughly the residual air after metals had been calcined.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He showed that this residual air supported neither combustion nor respiration and that approximately five volumes of this air added to one volume of the dephlogisticated air gave common atmospheric air.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Common air was then a mixture of two distinct chemical species with quite different properties.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Thus when the revised version of the Easter Memoir was published in 1778, Lavoisier no longer stated that the principle which combined with metals on calcination was just common air but "nothing else than the healthiest and purest part of the air" or the "eminently respirable part of the air".
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The same year he coined the name oxygen for this constituent of the air, from the Greek words meaning "acid former".
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He was struck by the fact that the combustion products of such nonmetals as sulfur, phosphorus, charcoal, and nitrogen were acidic.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He held that all acids contained oxygen and that oxygen was therefore the acidifying principle.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's chemical research between 1772 and 1778 was largely concerned with developing his own new theory of combustion.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In 1783 he read to the academy his paper entitled *Réflexions sur le phlogistique* (Reflections on Phlogiston), a full-scale attack on the current phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] That year Lavoisier also began a series of experiments on the composition of water which were to prove an important capstone to his combustion theory and win many converts to it.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Many investigators had been experimenting with the combination of Henry Cavendish's inflammable air, now known as hydrogen, with "dephlogisticated air" (air in the process of combustion, now known to be oxygen) by electrically sparking mixtures of the gases.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] All of the researchers noted Cavendish's production of pure water by burning hydrogen in oxygen, but they interpreted the reaction in varying ways within the framework of phlogiston theory.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier learned of Cavendish's experiment in June 1783 via Charles Blagden (before the results were published in 1784), and immediately recognized water as the oxide of a "hydrogenerative" gas.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In cooperation with Laplace, Lavoisier synthesized water by burning jets of hydrogen and oxygen in a bell jar over mercury.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The quantitative results were good enough to support the contention that water was not an element, as had been thought for over 2,000 years, but a compound of two gases, hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The interpretation of water as a compound explained the inflammable air generated from dissolving metals in acids (hydrogen produced when water decomposes) and the reduction of calces by inflammable air (a combination of gas from calx with hydrogen to form water).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Despite these experiments, Lavoisier's antiphlogistic approach remained unaccepted by many other chemists.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier labored to provide definitive proof of the composition of water, attempting to use this in support of his theory.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Working with Jean-Baptiste Meusnier, Lavoisier passed water through a red-hot iron gun barrel, allowing the oxygen to form an oxide with the iron and the hydrogen to emerge from the end of the pipe.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He submitted his findings of the composition of water to the Académie des Sciences in April 1784, reporting his figures to eight decimal places.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Opposition responded to this further experimentation by stating that Lavoisier continued to draw the incorrect conclusions and that his experiment demonstrated the displacement of phlogiston from iron by the combination of water with the metal.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier developed a new apparatus which used a pneumatic trough, a set of balances, a thermometer, and a barometer, all calibrated carefully.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Thirty savants were invited to witness the decomposition and synthesis of water using this apparatus, convincing many who attended of the correctness of Lavoisier's theories.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This demonstration established water as a compound of oxygen and hydrogen with great certainty for those who viewed it.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The dissemination of the experiment, however, proved subpar, as it lacked the details to properly display the amount of precision taken in the measurements.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The paper ended with a hasty statement that the experiment was "more than sufficient to lay hold of the certainty of the proposition" of the composition of water and stated that the methods used in the experiment would unite chemistry with the other physical sciences and advance discoveries.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier employed the new nomenclature in his *Traité élémentaire de chimie* (*Elementary Treatise on Chemistry*), published in 1789.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This work represents the synthesis of Lavoisier's contribution to chemistry and can be considered the first modern textbook on the subject.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The core of the work was the oxygen theory, and the work became a most effective vehicle for the transmission of the new doctrines.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] It presented a unified view of new theories of chemistry, contained a clear statement of the law of conservation of mass, and denied the existence of phlogiston.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This text clarified the concept of an element as a substance that could not be broken down by any known method of chemical analysis and presented Lavoisier's theory of the formation of chemical compounds from elements.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] It remains a classic in the history of science.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] While many leading chemists of the time refused to accept Lavoisier's new ideas, demand for *Traité élémentaire* as a textbook in Edinburgh was sufficient to merit translation into English within about a year of its French publication.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In any event, the *Traité élémentaire* was sufficiently sound to convince the next generation.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The relationship between combustion and respiration had long been recognized from the essential role which air played in both processes.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was almost obliged, therefore, to extend his new theory of combustion to include the area of respiration physiology.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] His first memoirs on this topic were read to the Academy of Sciences in 1777, but his most significant contribution to this field was made in the winter of 1782–1783 in association with Laplace.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The result of this work was published in a memoir, "On Heat." Lavoisier and Laplace designed an ice calorimeter apparatus for measuring the amount of heat given off during combustion or respiration.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The outer shell of the calorimeter was packed with snow, which melted to maintain a constant temperature of 0 °C around an inner shell filled with ice.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier stated, *"la respiration est donc une combustion,"* that is, respiratory gas exchange is a combustion, like that of a candle burning.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] This continuous slow combustion, which they supposed took place in the lungs, enabled the living animal to maintain its body temperature above that of its surroundings, thus accounting for the puzzling phenomenon of animal heat.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier continued these respiration experiments in 1789–1790 in cooperation with Armand Seguin.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] They designed an ambitious set of experiments to study the whole process of body metabolism and respiration using Seguin as a human guinea pig in the experiments.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Their work was only partially completed and published because of the Revolution's disruption, but Lavoisier's pioneering work in this field inspired similar research on physiological processes for generations.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's fundamental contributions to chemistry were a result of a conscious effort to fit all experiments into the framework of a single theory.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He established the consistent use of the chemical balance, used oxygen to overthrow the phlogiston theory, and developed a new system of chemical nomenclature which held that oxygen was an essential constituent of all acids (which later turned out to be erroneous).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also did early research in physical chemistry and thermodynamics in joint experiments with Laplace.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] They used a calorimeter to estimate the heat evolved per unit of carbon dioxide produced, eventually finding the same ratio for a flame and animals, indicating that animals produced energy by a type of combustion reaction.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also contributed to early ideas on composition and chemical changes by stating the radical theory, believing that radicals, which function as a single group in a chemical process, combine with oxygen in reactions.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He also introduced the possibility of allotropy in chemical elements when he discovered that diamond is a crystalline form of carbon.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He was also responsible for the construction of the gasometer, an expensive instrument he used at his demonstrations.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] While he used his gasometer exclusively for these, he also created smaller, cheaper, more practical gasometers that worked with a sufficient degree of precision that more chemists could recreate.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Overall, his contributions are considered the most important in advancing chemistry to the level reached in physics and mathematics during the 18th century.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Following his death, a collection comprising most of his scientific manuscripts and instruments was established by his relatives at the Château de la Canière in Puy-de-Dôme.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Mount Lavoisier in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] In the Breaking Bad season 5 episode “Say My Name” (episode 7), Walter White tells Todd Alquist, “I don’t need you to be Antoine Lavoisier,” meaning that Todd does not need to be an expert to assist with cooking methamphetamine.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] During his lifetime, Lavoisier was awarded a gold medal by the King of France for his work on urban street lighting (1766), and was appointed to the French Academy of Sciences (1768).
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1775.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's work was recognized as an International Historic Chemical Landmark by the American Chemical Society, Académie des sciences de L'institut de France and the Société Chimique de France in 1999.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] The prize, which includes a medal, is given jointly by the Fondation de la Maison de la Chimie in Paris, France and the Science History Institute in Philadelphia, PA, USA.
[src:heat/antoine-lavoisier] "Lavoisier's "Reflections on phlogiston" II: On the nature of heat".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:heat/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:heat/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC One and BBC Two are the flagship television channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Others include the youth channel BBC Three, cultural and documentary channel BBC Four, the British and international variations of the BBC News channel, parliamentary channel BBC Parliament, and two children's channels, CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Digital television is now entrenched in the UK, with analogue transmission completely phased out as of December 2012.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC One is a regionalised TV service which provides opt-outs throughout the day for local news and other local programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] These variations are more pronounced in the BBC "Nations", i.e.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, where the presentation is mostly carried out locally on BBC One and Two, and where programme schedules can vary considerably from that of the network.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Two variations exist in the Nations; however, English regions today rarely have the option to opt out as regional programming now exists only on BBC One.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2019, the Scottish variation of BBC Two ceased operation and was replaced with the networked version in favour of a new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Two was the first channel to be transmitted on 625 lines, in 1964.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It then carried a small-scale regular colour service from 1967.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] A new Scottish Gaelic television channel, BBC Alba, was launched in September 2008.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It is also the first multi-genre channel to come entirely from Scotland with almost all of its programmes made in Scotland.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The service was initially available only via satellite but since June 2011 has been available to viewers in Scotland on Freeview and cable television.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC currently operates HD simulcasts of all its nationwide channels with the exception of BBC Parliament.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Until 26 March 2013, a separate channel called BBC HD was available, in place of BBC Two HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It launched on 15 May 2006, following a 12-month trial of the broadcasts.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It became a proper channel in 2007, and screened HD programmes as simulcasts of the main network, or as repeats.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The corporation has been producing programmes in the format for many years, and stated that it hoped to produce 100% of new programmes in HDTV by 2010.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] On 3 November 2010, a high-definition simulcast of BBC One was launched, entitled BBC One HD, and BBC Two HD launched on 26 March 2013, replacing BBC HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Scotland's new television channel, BBC Scotland, launched in February 2019.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland, the BBC channels are available in a number of ways.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In these countries digital and cable operators carry a range of BBC channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since 1975 the BBC has also provided its TV programmes to the British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS), allowing members of UK military serving abroad to watch them on four dedicated TV channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] From 27 March 2013, BFBS will carry versions of BBC One and BBC Two, which will include children's programming from CBBC, as well as carrying programming from BBC Three on a new channel called BFBS Extra.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since 2008 all BBC channels are available to watch online through the BBC iPlayer service.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This online streaming ability came about following experiments with live streaming, involving streaming certain channels in the UK.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In February 2014, Director-General Tony Hall announced that the corporation needed to save £100 million.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In March 2014, the BBC confirmed plans for BBC Three to become an internet-only channel.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] An earlier ten months of listings are to be obtained from other sources.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] They identified about five million programmes, involving 8.5 million actors, presenters, writers and technical staff.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The Genome project was opened to public access on 15 October 2014, with corrections to OCR errors and changes to advertised schedules being crowdsourced.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has ten radio stations serving the whole of the UK, a further seven stations in the "national regions" (Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland), and 39 other local stations serving defined areas of England.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Of the ten national stations, five are major stations and are available on FM or AM as well as on DAB and online.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to these five stations, the BBC runs a further five stations that broadcast on DAB and online only.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] These stations supplement and expand on the big five stations, and were launched in 2002.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1Xtra sisters Radio 1, and broadcasts new Black music and urban tracks.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra sisters 5 Live and offers extra sport analysis, including broadcasting sports that previously were not covered.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 6 Music offers alternative music genres and is notable as a platform for new artists.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 7, later renamed BBC Radio 4 Extra, provides archive drama, comedy and children's programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The final station is the BBC Asian Network, providing music, talk and news to this section of the community.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This station evolved out of Local radio stations serving certain areas, and as such this station is available on medium wave frequency in some areas of the Midlands.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As well as the national stations, the BBC also provides 40 BBC Local Radio stations in England and the Channel Islands, each named for and covering a particular city and its surrounding area (e.g.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Bristol), county or region (e.g.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Three Counties Radio), or geographical area (e.g.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Solent covering the central south coast).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] A further six stations broadcast in what the BBC terms "the national regions": Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] These are BBC Radio Wales (in English), BBC Radio Cymru (in Welsh), BBC Radio Scotland (in English), BBC Radio nan Gàidheal (in Scottish Gaelic), BBC Radio Ulster, and BBC Radio Foyle, the latter being an opt-out station from Radio Ulster for the north-west of Northern Ireland.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC's UK national channels are also broadcast in the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man (although these Crown Dependencies are outside the UK), and in the former there are two local stations – BBC Radio Guernsey and BBC Radio Jersey.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] There is no BBC local radio station, however, in the Isle of Man, partly because the island has long been served by the popular independent commercial station, Manx Radio, which predates the existence of BBC Local Radio.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC services in the dependencies are financed from television licence fees which are set at the same level as those payable in the UK, although collected locally.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This is the subject of some controversy in the Isle of Man since, as well as having no BBC Local Radio service, the island also lacks a local television news service analogous to that provided by BBC Channel Islands.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It is broadcast worldwide on shortwave radio, DAB and online and has an estimated weekly audience of 192 million, and its websites have an audience of 38 million people per week.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since 2005, it is also available on DAB in the UK, a step not taken before, due to the way it is funded.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Following the Government's spending review in 2011, the service was funded for the first time through the Licence fee.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In recent years, some services of the World Service have been reduced: the Thai service ended in 2006, as did the Eastern European languages.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Resources were diverted instead into the new BBC News Arabic.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Historically the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster based in the UK mainland until 1967, when University Radio York, then under the name *Radio York*, was launched as the first, and now oldest, legal independent radio station in the country.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] However, the BBC did not enjoy a complete monopoly before this, as several Continental stations, such as Radio Luxembourg, had broadcast programmes in English to Britain since the 1930s and the Isle of Man-based Manx Radio began in 1964.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Today, despite the advent of commercial broadcasting, BBC radio stations remain among the most listened-to in the country.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Radio 2 has the largest audience share (up to 16.8% in 2011–12) and Radios 1 and 4 ranked second and third in terms of weekly reach.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC programming is also available to other services and in other countries.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since 1943, the BBC has provided radio programming to the British Forces Broadcasting Service, which broadcasts in countries where British troops are stationed.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1 is also carried in Canada on SiriusXM (online streaming only).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC is a patron of the Radio Academy, a registered UK charity that promotes excellence in broadcasting.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC News is the largest broadcast news gathering operation in the world, providing services to BBC domestic radio as well as television networks such as the BBC News, BBC Parliament and BBC News International.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to this, news stories are available on the BBC Red Button service and BBC News Online.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to this, the BBC has been developing new ways to access BBC News and as a result, has launched the service on BBC Mobile, making it accessible to mobile phones and PDAs, as well as developing alerts by email, on digital television, and on computers through a desktop alert.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Ratings figures suggest that during major incidents such as the 7 July 2005 London bombings or royal events, the UK audience overwhelmingly turns to the BBC's coverage as opposed to its commercial rivals.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] On 7 July 2005, the day there were a series of coordinated bomb blasts on London's public transport system, the BBC Online website recorded an all time bandwidth peak of 11 Gb/s at 12.00 on 7 July.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC News received some 1 billion total hits on the day of the event (including all images, text, and HTML), serving some 5.5 terabytes of data.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] At peak times during the day, there were 40,000-page requests per second for the BBC News website.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The previous day's announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics being awarded to London caused a peak of about 5 Gbit/s.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The previous all-time high at BBC Online was caused by the announcement of the Michael Jackson verdict, which used 7.2 Gbit/s.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC's online presence includes a comprehensive news website and archive.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC's first official online service was the BBC Networking Club, which was launched on 11 May 1994.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The service was subsequently relaunched as BBC Online in 1997, before being renamed BBCi, then bbc.co.uk, before it was rebranded back as BBC Online.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The website is funded by the Licence fee, but uses GeoIP technology, allowing advertisements to be carried on the site when viewed outside of the UK.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC claims the site to be "Europe's most popular content-based site" and states that 13.2 million people in the UK visit the site's more than two million pages each day.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The centre of the website is the Homepage, which features a modular layout.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Users can choose which modules, and which information, is displayed on their homepage, allowing the user to customise it.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This system was first launched in December 2007, becoming permanent in February 2008, and has undergone a few aesthetical changes since then.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The home page then has links to other micro-sites, such as BBC News Online, Sport, Weather, TV, and Radio.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As part of the site, every programme on BBC Television or Radio is given its own page, with bigger programmes getting their own micro-site, and as a result it is often common for viewers and listeners to be told URLs for the programme website.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allowed legal downloads of selected archive material via the internet.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has often included learning as part of its online service, running services such as BBC Jam, Learning Zone Class Clips and also runs services such as BBC WebWise and First Click which are designed to teach people how to use the internet.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Jam was a free online service, delivered through broadband and narrowband connections, providing high-quality interactive resources designed to stimulate learning at home and at school.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Initial content was made available in January 2006; however, BBC Jam was suspended on 20 March 2007 due to allegations made to the European Commission that it was damaging the interests of the commercial sector of the industry.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In recent years some major on-line companies and politicians have complained that BBC Online receives too much funding from the television licence, meaning that other websites are unable to compete with the vast amount of advertising-free on-line content available on BBC Online.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Some have proposed that the amount of licence fee money spent on BBC Online should be reduced—either being replaced with funding from advertisements or subscriptions, or a reduction in the amount of content available on the site.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In response to this the BBC carried out an investigation, and has now set in motion a plan to change the way it provides its online services.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Online will now attempt to fill in gaps in the market, and will guide users to other websites for currently existing market provision.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] (For example, instead of providing local events information and timetables, users will be guided to outside websites already providing that information.) Part of this plan included the BBC closing some of its websites, and rediverting money to redevelop other parts.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network, as part of Mark Thompson's plans to make "a smaller, fitter BBC for the digital age".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Red Button is the brand name for the BBC's interactive television services, which are available through Freeview (digital terrestrial), as well as Freesat, Sky UK (satellite), and Virgin Media (cable).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Unlike Ceefax, the service's analogue counterpart, BBC Red Button is able to display full-colour graphics, photographs, and video, as well as programmes and can be accessed from any BBC channel.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The service carries News, Weather and Sport 24 hours a day, but also provides extra features related to programmes specific at that time.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Examples include viewers to play along at home to gameshows, to give, voice and vote on opinions to issues, as used alongside programmes such as *Question Time*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] At some points in the year, when multiple sporting events occur, some coverage of less mainstream sports or games are frequently placed on the Red Button for viewers to watch.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Frequently, other features are added unrelated to programmes being broadcast at that time, such as the broadcast of the *Doctor Who* animated episode *Dreamland* in November 2009.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It also buys a selected number of broadcasts from the Ulster Orchestra in Belfast and the BBC Big Band.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC Proms have been produced by the BBC every year since 1927, stepping in to fund the popular eight-week summer classical music festival when music publishers Chappell and Co withdrew their support.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 1930, the newly formed BBC Symphony Orchestra gave all 49 Proms, and have performed at every Last Night of the Proms since then.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The Proms have been held at the Royal Albert Hall since 1941, and the BBC's orchestras and choirs are the backbone of the festival, giving about 40% to 50% of all performances each season.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Many famous musicians of every genre have played at the BBC, such as The Beatles (*Live at the BBC* is one of their many albums).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC is also responsible for the broadcast of Glastonbury Festival, Reading and Leeds Festivals and United Kingdom coverage of the Eurovision Song Contest, a show with which the broadcaster has been associated for over 60 years.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates the division of BBC Audiobooks sometimes found in association with Chivers Audiobooks.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC operates other ventures as well as its broadcasting arm.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to broadcasting output on television and radio, some programmes are also displayed on the BBC Big Screens in several central-city locations.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC and the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office also jointly run BBC Monitoring, which monitors radio, television, the press and the internet worldwide.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The National Museum of Computing at Bletchley Park uses BBC Micros as part of a scheme to educate school children about computer programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 1951, in conjunction with Oxford University Press, the BBC published *The BBC Hymn Book*, intended to be used by radio listeners to follow hymns being broadcast.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The book was published both with and without music, the music edition being entitled *The BBC Hymn Book with Music*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC provided the world's first teletext service called Ceefax (near-homophonous with "See Facts") from 23 September 1974 until 23 October 2012 on the BBC1 analogue channel, then later on BBC2.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It showed informational pages, such as news, sport, and the weather.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] From New Year's Eve, 1974, ITV's Oracle tried to compete with Ceefax.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] During its lifetime, Ceefax attracted millions of viewers, right up until 2012, prior to the digital switchover in the United Kingdom.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Since then, the BBC's Red Button Service has provided a digital information system that replaced Ceefax.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2016 the BBC, in partnership with fellow UK broadcasters ITV and Channel 4 (the latter later withdrew from the project), set up 'project kangaroo' to develop an international online streaming service to rival services such as Netflix and Hulu.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] During the development stages 'Britflix' was touted as a potential name.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] However, the service eventually launched as BritBox in March 2017.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The online platform shows a catalogue of classic BBC and ITV shows, as well as making a number of programmes available shortly after their UK broadcast.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As of 2021, BritBox is available in the UK, the US, Canada, Australia, and, more recently, South Africa, with the potential availability for new markets in the future.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Studios is the wholly owned commercial subsidiary of the BBC, responsible for the commercial exploitation of BBC programmes and other properties, including a number of television stations throughout the world.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It was formed in 2018 after the merger of the BBC's commercial production arm and the BBC's commercial international distribution arm, BBC Worldwide, with the latter formed in 1995 following the restructuring of its predecessor, BBC Enterprises.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Prior to this, the selling of BBC television programmes was at first handled in 1958 with the establishment of a business manager post.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This expanded until the establishment of the Television Promotions (renamed Television Enterprises) department in 1960 under a general manager.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The company owns and administers a number of commercial stations around the world operating in a number of territories and on a number of different platforms.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] These include BBC UKTV for the Australasia region, and formerly BBC America (now fully owned by AMC Networks).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The company airs two channels aimed at children, an international CBeebies channel and BBC Kids, a joint venture with Knowledge Network Corporation.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The company also runs BBC Earth, which distributes the BBC's natural history content to countries outside the UK, and BBC Lifestyle, broadcasting programmes based on themes of Food, Style and Wellbeing.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to this, BBC Studios ran an international version of the channel BBC HD.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also distributes the 24-hour international news channel BBC News.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The station is separate from BBC Studios to maintain the station's neutral point of view, but is distributed by BBC Studios.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The channel itself is the oldest surviving entity of its kind, and has 50 foreign news bureaus and correspondents in nearly all countries in the world.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] As officially surveyed, it is available to more than 294 million households, significantly more than CNN's estimated 200 million.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to these international channels, BBC Studios also owns the UKTV network of seven channels.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] These channels contain BBC archive programming to be rebroadcast on their respective channels: Alibi, crime dramas; Dave (slogan: "The Home of Witty Banter"); Drama, drama, launched in 2013; Eden, nature; Gold, comedy; W, Entertainment; and Yesterday, history programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to these channels, many BBC programmes are sold via BBC Studios to foreign television stations with comedy, documentaries, crime dramas (such as *Luther* and *Peaky Blinders*) and historical drama productions being the most popular.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC's most successful reality television show format, *Strictly Come Dancing*—under the title *Dancing with the Stars*—has been exported to 60 other countries.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Shows commissioned and distributed by the BBC include the *Wallace & Gromit* animated comedy short films *The Wrong Trousers* and *A Close Shave*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC television news also appears nightly on many PBS stations in the US, as do reruns of BBC programmes such as *EastEnders*, and in New Zealand on TVNZ 1.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In addition to programming, BBC Studios produces material to accompany programmes.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The company maintained the publishing arm of the BBC, BBC Magazines, which published the *Radio Times*; first published by the BBC on 28 September 1923, it is the world's first broadcast listings magazine.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] *Radio Times* covers all British television and radio programming schedules, and the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11,220,666 copies, which the *Guinness World Records* certified as the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Other magazines that support BBC programming include *BBC Top Gear*, *BBC Good Food*, *BBC Sky at Night*, *BBC History*, *BBC Wildlife* and *BBC Music*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Magazines was sold to Exponent Private Equity in 2011, which merged it with Origin Publishing (previously owned by BBC Worldwide between 2004 and 2006) to form Immediate Media Company.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also publishes books, to accompany programmes such as *Sherlock* and *Doctor Who* under the BBC Books brand, a publishing imprint majority owned by Random House.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Archive programming and classical music recordings are sold under the brand BBC Legends.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Until the development, popularisation, and domination of television, radio was the broadcast medium upon which people in the United Kingdom relied.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It "reached into every home in the land, and simultaneously united the nation, an important factor during the Second World War".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC introduced the world's first "high-definition" 405-line television service in 1936.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It suspended its television service during the Second World War and until 1946, but remained the only television broadcaster in the UK until 1955, when Independent Television (ITV) began operating.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] This heralded the transformation of television into a popular and dominant medium.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Nevertheless, "throughout the 1950s radio still remained the dominant source of broadcast comedy".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Further, the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster until 1968 (when University Radio York obtained its first licence).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Despite the advent of commercial television and radio, with competition from ITV, Channel 4 and Sky, the BBC has remained one of the main elements in British popular culture through its obligation to produce TV and radio programmes for mass audiences.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] However, the arrival of BBC2 allowed the BBC also to make programmes for minority interests in drama, documentaries, current affairs, entertainment, and sport.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Described as television's first "watercooler moment" by *The Telegraph*, the BBC's 1954 adaptation of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* made a dramatic impact on a fledgling television audience who were horrified by the graphic depiction of a totalitarian regime controlling the population.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Making his BBC debut in 1949, Benny Hill with *The Benny Hill Show* became the first British comedian to become famous via television.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Popular comedy duos on the BBC include Morecambe and Wise (whose show debuted in 1968) and The Two Ronnies (debuting in 1971).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Black comedy sitcom *Blackadder*, starring Rowan Atkinson as the title character, ran for four series between 1983 and 1989.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The British Academy Film Awards (BAFTAs) was first broadcast on the BBC in 1956, with Vivien Leigh as the host.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The television equivalent, the British Academy Television Awards, has been screened exclusively on the BBC since a 2007 awards ceremony that included wins for Jim Broadbent (Best actor) and Ricky Gervais (Best comedy performance).
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The term "BBC English" was used as an alternative name for Received Pronunciation, and the *English Pronouncing Dictionary* uses the term "BBC Pronunciation" to label its recommendations.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] However, the BBC itself now makes more use of regional accents to reflect the diversity of the UK, while continuing to expect clarity and fluency of its presenters.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] From its "starchy" beginnings, the BBC has also become more inclusive, and now attempts to accommodate the interests of all strata of society and all minorities, because they all pay the licence fee.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Older domestic UK audiences often refer to the BBC as "the Beeb", a nickname coined by Peter Sellers during a 1972 reunion of the 1950s BBC radio comedy *The Goon Show*, when he referred to the "Beeb Beeb Ceeb".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It was then shortened and popularised by radio DJ Kenny Everett.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] David Bowie's recording sessions at the BBC were released as *Bowie at the Beeb*, while Queen's BBC recording sessions were released as *At the Beeb*.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The term "Auntie" for the BBC is often credited to radio disc-jockey Jack Jackson.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] To celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the BBC the song "Auntie" was released in 1972.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It also featured in the title of the BBC's blooper show, *Auntie's Bloomers*, which was presented by Terry Wogan from 1991 to 2001.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The two nicknames have also been used together as "Auntie Beeb".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Throughout its existence the BBC has faced numerous accusations regarding many topics: the Iraq war, the Gaza war, politics, ethics and religion, as well as funding and staffing.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It also has been involved in numerous controversies because of its coverage of specific news stories and programming.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has been accused repeatedly of anti-Israel bias, and to a greater extent anti-Israel Defense Force bias.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has long faced accusations of liberal and left-wing bias.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Accusations of a bias against the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party were often made against the BBC by members of that government, with Margaret Thatcher herself considering the broadcaster's news coverage to be biased and irresponsible.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2011, Peter Sissons, a main news presenter at the BBC from 1989 to 2009, said that "at the core of the BBC, in its very DNA, is a way of thinking that is firmly of the Left".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Another BBC presenter, Andrew Marr, commented that "the BBC is not impartial or neutral.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It has a liberal bias, not so much a party-political bias.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] It is better expressed as a cultural liberal bias." Former BBC director Roger Mosey classified it as "liberal defensive".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In 2022, the BBC chairman, Richard Sharp, said that the BBC "does have a liberal bias" and that the institution is "fighting against it".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In November 2025, allegations by *The Daily Telegraph* that the BBC had deceptively spliced a Donald Trump speech preceding the January 6 United States Capitol attack in a documentary led to several BBC executives resigning, including the head of the BBC.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Writing for *The Guardian* in 2018, the left-wing columnist Owen Jones stated "the truth is the BBC is stacked full of rightwingers," and cited as an example of bias its employment of "ultra-Thatcherite" Andrew Neil as a politics presenter.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] In November 2025, LibDem leader Ed Davey called for Gibb's removal from the BBC board because of Gibb's alleged role in the 2025 BBC editorial bias controversy.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] A 2018 opinion poll by BMG Research found that 40% of the British public thought that the BBC was politically partisan, with a nearly even split between those who believed it leaned to the left or right.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Additionally oft-cited are its policy of "balancing" appearances by transgender people with activists from gender-critical groups, its manual of style which requires any allegations of transphobia to be challenged by the news presenter, and its policy against using the term "cisgender".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] The BBC has also been accused by gender-critical groups and BBC staff of having a pro-trans bias, primarily for "failing to make it clear that transgender women are biological males".
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Such accusations have alleged that the BBC's LGBT desk has been "captured by a small group of people" intent on promoting a pro-trans agenda.
[src:heat/bbc-p02] Shortly thereafter, the BBC began running articles referring to trans women as "biological males who identify as women".
[src:heat/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, **heat** is defined as energy in transfer between a body and its surroundings, other than through thermodynamic work or through transfer of matter.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Rather than by mechanical or other effects in the surroundings, thermodynamic work is defined through changes in the system’s macroscopic state variables, in conjugate pairs such as pressure and volume, or magnetisation and magnetic field strength.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The thermodynamic definition of heat is by exclusion of other defined modes of transfer in order to ensure a strict logical distinction.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In the process of transfer, heat is not necessarily conserved, but can be generated (though not destroyed) by friction.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, temperature is defined in macroscopic terms, through the concepts of heat and work.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat is not a state variable or state function; it is a process quantity.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A thermodynamic system does not *contain* heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat can enter or leave a body of matter by thermal conduction, by electromagnetic radiation, or through friction due to macroscopic mechanical movement.
[src:heat/heat-p01] When heat is generated by friction, it may end up partly in each of the two engaged bodies.
[src:heat/heat-p01] When energy enters or leaves a body through transfer of matter, it cannot be resolved uniquely into work and heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] By assuming conservation of heat in a transfer, calorimetry measures it by its effect on the states of interacting bodies, for example, by the amount of ice melted or by change in temperature of a body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In the International System of Units (SI), the unit of measurement for heat is the joule (J).
[src:heat/heat-p01] As a form of energy, heat has the unit joule (J) in the International System of Units (SI).
[src:heat/heat-p01] In addition, many applied branches of engineering use other, traditional units, such as the British thermal unit (BTU) and the calorie.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The standard unit for the rate of heating is the watt (W), defined as one joule per second.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The symbol Q for heat was introduced by Rudolf Clausius and Macquorn Rankine in c.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat released by a system into its surroundings is by convention, as a contributor to internal energy, a negative quantity (*Q* < 0); when a system absorbs heat from its surroundings, it is positive (*Q* > 0).
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat transfer rate, or heat flow per unit time, is denoted by ${\dot {Q}}$ , but it is not a time derivative of a function of state (which can also be written with the dot notation) since heat is not a function of state.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat flux is defined as rate of heat transfer per unit cross-sectional area (watts per square metre).
[src:heat/heat-p01] In ordinary language, English 'heat' or 'warmth', just as French *chaleur*, German *Hitze* or *Wärme*, Latin *calor*, Greek θάλπος, etc. refers to either thermal energy or temperature, or the human perception of these.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Later, *chaleur* (as used by Sadi Carnot), 'heat', and *Wärme* became equivalents also as specific scientific terms at an early stage of thermodynamics.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Speculation on 'heat' as a separate form of matter has a long history, involving the phlogiston theory, the caloric theory, and fire.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Many careful and accurate historical experiments practically exclude friction, mechanical and thermodynamic work and matter transfer, investigating transfer of energy only by thermal conduction and radiation.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such experiments give impressive rational support to the caloric theory of heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] To account also for changes of internal energy due to friction, and mechanical and thermodynamic work, the caloric theory was, around the end of the eighteenth century, replaced by the "mechanical" theory of heat, which is accepted today.
[src:heat/heat-p01] As scientists of the early modern age began to adopt the view that matter consists of particles, a close relationship between heat and the motion of those particles was widely surmised, or even the equivalency of the concepts, boldly expressed by the English philosopher Francis Bacon in 1620.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Galileo wrote that heat and pressure are apparent properties only, caused by the movement of particles, which is a real phenomenon.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1665, and again in 1681, English polymath Robert Hooke reiterated that heat is nothing but the motion of the constituent particles of objects, and in 1675, his colleague, Anglo-Irish scientist Robert Boyle repeated that this motion is what heat consists of.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat has been discussed in ordinary language by philosophers.
[src:heat/heat-p01] When Bacon, Galileo, Hooke, Boyle and Locke wrote "heat", they might more have referred to what we would now call "temperature".
[src:heat/heat-p01] No clear distinction was made between heat and temperature until the mid-18th century, nor between the internal energy of a body and the transfer of energy as heat until the mid-19th century.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Locke's description of heat was repeatedly quoted by English physicist James Prescott Joule.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Also the transfer of heat was explained by the motion of particles.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The theory was developed in academic publications in French, English and German.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Unstated distinctions between heat and “hotness” may be very old, heat seen as something dependent on the *quantity* of a hot substance, “heat”, vaguely perhaps distinct from the *quality* of "hotness".
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1723, the English mathematician Brook Taylor measured the temperature—the expansion of the liquid in a thermometer—of mixtures of various amounts of hot water in cold water.
[src:heat/heat-p01] As expected, the increase in temperature was in proportion to the proportion of hot water in the mixture.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The distinction between heat and temperature is implicitly expressed in the last sentence of his report.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1748, an account was published in *The Edinburgh Physical and Literary Essays* of an experiment by the Scottish physician and chemist William Cullen.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Cullen had used an air pump to lower the pressure in a container with diethyl ether.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The ether boiled, while no heat was withdrawn from it, and its temperature decreased.
[src:heat/heat-p01] And in 1758 on a warm day in Cambridge, England, Benjamin Franklin and fellow scientist John Hadley experimented by continually wetting the ball of a mercury thermometer with ether and using bellows to evaporate the ether.
[src:heat/heat-p01] With each subsequent evaporation, the thermometer read a lower temperature, eventually reaching 7 °F (−14 °C).
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1756 or soon thereafter, Joseph Black, Cullen’s friend and former assistant, began an extensive study of heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1760 Black realized that when two different substances of equal mass but different temperatures are mixed, the changes in number of degrees in the two substances differ, though the heat gained by the cooler substance and lost by the hotter is the same.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Black related an experiment conducted by Daniel Gabriel Fahrenheit on behalf of Dutch physician Herman Boerhaave.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This clarified the distinction between heat and temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It also introduced the concept of specific heat capacity, being different for different substances.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In his investigations of specific heat, Black used a unit of heat he called "degrees of heat"—as opposed to just "degrees" [of temperature].
[src:heat/heat-p01] This unit was context-dependent and could only be used when circumstances were identical.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It was based on change in temperature multiplied by the mass of the substance involved.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It was known that when the air temperature rises above freezing—air then becoming the obvious heat source—snow melts very slowly and the temperature of the melted snow is close to its freezing point.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1757, Black started to investigate if heat, therefore, was required for the melting of a solid, independent of any rise in temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] As far Black knew, the general view at that time was that melting was inevitably accompanied by a small increase in temperature, and that no additional heat was needed beyond what this increase in temperature would require in itself.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Soon, however, Black was able to show that much more heat was required during melting than could be explained by any increase in temperature alone.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He was also able to show that heat is *released* by a liquid during its freezing; again, much more than could be explained by the decrease of its temperature alone.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1762, Black announced the following research and results to a society of professors at the University of Glasgow.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Black had placed equal masses of ice at 32 °F (0 °C) and water at 33 °F (0.6 °C) respectively in two identical, well separated containers.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The water and the ice were both evenly heated to 40 °F by the air in the room, which was at a constant 47 °F (8 °C).
[src:heat/heat-p01] The water had therefore received 40 – 33 = 7 “degrees of heat”.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The ice had been heated for 21 times longer and had therefore received 7 × 21 = 147 “degrees of heat”.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The temperature of the ice had increased by 8 °F.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The ice had thus absorbed 8 “degrees of heat”, which Black called *sensible heat*, manifest as temperature change, which could be felt and measured.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In addition to that, 147 – 8 = 139 “degrees of heat” were absorbed as *latent heat*, manifest as phase change rather than as temperature change.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Black next showed that a water temperature of 176 °F was needed to melt an equal mass of ice until it was all 32 °F.
[src:heat/heat-p01] So now 176 – 32 = 144 “degrees of heat” seemed to be needed to melt the ice.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The modern value for the heat of fusion of ice would be 143 “degrees of heat” on the same scale (79.5 “degrees of heat Celsius”).
[src:heat/heat-p01] Finally, Black increased the temperature of a mass of water, then vaporized an equal mass of water by even heating.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He showed that 830 “degrees of heat” was needed for the vaporization; again based on the time required.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The modern value for the heat of vaporization of water would be 967 “degrees of heat” on the same scale.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A calorimeter is a device used for measuring heat capacity, as well as the heat absorbed or released in chemical reactions or physical changes.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1780, French chemist Antoine Lavoisier used such an apparatus—which he named 'calorimeter'—to investigate the heat released by respiration, by observing how this heat melted snow surrounding his apparatus.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A so called *ice calorimeter* was used 1782–83 by Lavoisier and his colleague Pierre-Simon Laplace to measure the heat released in various chemical reactions.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The heat so released melted a specific amount of ice, and the heat required for the melting of a certain amount of ice was known beforehand.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The modern understanding of heat is often partly attributed to Thompson's 1798 mechanical theory of heat ("An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction"), postulating a mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A collaboration between Nicolas Clément and Sadi Carnot (*Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*) in the 1820s had some related thinking along similar lines.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In 1842, Julius Robert Mayer frictionally generated heat in paper pulp and measured the temperature rise.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The theory of classical thermodynamics matured in the 1850s to 1860s.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The process function Q was introduced by Rudolf Clausius in 1850.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Clausius described it with the German compound *Wärmemenge*, translated as "amount of heat".
[src:heat/heat-p01] Bryan published an investigation of the foundations of thermodynamics, *Thermodynamics: an Introductory Treatise dealing mainly with First Principles and their Direct Applications*, B.G.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Bryan was writing when thermodynamics had been established empirically, but people were still interested to specify its logical structure.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The 1909 work of Carathéodory also belongs to this historical era.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Bryan was a physicist while Carathéodory was a mathematician.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Bryan started his treatise with an introductory chapter on the notions of heat and of temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He gives an example of where the notion of heating as raising a body's temperature contradicts the notion of heating as imparting a quantity of heat to that body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He defined an adiabatic transformation as one in which the body neither gains nor loses heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This is not the same as defining an adiabatic transformation as one that occurs to a body enclosed by walls impermeable to radiation and conduction.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He recognized calorimetry as a way of measuring quantity of heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He recognized water as having a *temperature of maximum density*.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This makes water unsuitable as a thermometric substance around that temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He intended to remind readers of why thermodynamicists preferred an absolute scale of temperature, independent of the properties of a particular thermometric substance.
[src:heat/heat-p01] His second chapter started with the recognition of friction as a source of heat, by Benjamin Thompson, by Humphry Davy, by Robert Mayer, and by James Prescott Joule.
[src:heat/heat-p01] When heat is transformed into work or conversely work is transformed into heat, the quantity of heat gained or lost is proportional to the quantity of work lost or gained.
[src:heat/heat-p01] If heat be measured in dynamical units the mechanical equivalent becomes equal to unity, and the equations of thermodynamics assume a simpler and more symmetrical form.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He explained how the caloric theory of Lavoisier and Laplace made sense in terms of pure calorimetry, though it failed to account for conversion of work into heat by such mechanisms as friction and conduction of electricity.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Having rationally defined quantity of heat, he went on to consider the second law, including the Kelvin definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Physical unreality of reversible processes.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In Nature all phenomena are irreversible in a greater or less degree.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In §47, on page 39, he stated the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In connection with irreversible phenomena the following axioms have to be assumed.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A perfectly reversible change cannot take place of itself; such a change can only be regarded as the limiting form of an irreversible change.
[src:heat/heat-p01] When two bodies act thermically on one another the quantities of heat gained by one and lost by the other are not necessarily equal.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In the case of bodies at a distance, heat may be taken from or given to the intervening medium.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Another important exception occurs when sliding takes place between two rough bodies in contact.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The algebraic sum of the works done is different from zero, because, although the action and reaction are equal and opposite the velocities of the parts of the bodies in contact are different.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Moreover, the work lost in the process does not increase the mutual potential energy of the system and there is no intervening medium between the bodies.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Unless the lost energy can be accounted for in other ways, (as when friction produces electrification), it follows from the Principle of Conservation of Energy that the algebraic sum of the quantities of heat gained by the two systems is equal to the quantity of work lost by friction.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This thought was echoed in some detail in 1941 by Bridgman.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A celebrated and frequent definition of heat in thermodynamics is based on the work of Carathéodory (1909), referring to processes in a closed system.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Carathéodory was responding to a suggestion by Max Born that he examine the logical structure of thermodynamics.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The internal energy *UX* of a body in an arbitrary state *X* can be determined by amounts of work adiabatically performed by the body on its surroundings when it starts from a reference state *O*.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such work is assessed through quantities defined in the surroundings of the body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is supposed that such work can be assessed accurately, without error due to friction in the surroundings; friction in the body is not excluded by this definition.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The adiabatic performance of work is defined in terms of adiabatic walls, which allow transfer of energy as work, but no other transfer, of energy or matter.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In particular they do not allow the passage of energy as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] According to this definition, work performed adiabatically is in general accompanied by friction within the thermodynamic system or body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] On the other hand, according to Carathéodory (1909), there also exist non-adiabatic, *diathermal* walls, which are postulated to be permeable only to heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] For the definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat, it is customarily envisaged that an arbitrary state of interest *Y* is reached from state *O* by a process with two components, one adiabatic and the other not adiabatic.
[src:heat/heat-p01] For convenience one may say that the adiabatic component was the sum of work done by the body through volume change through movement of the walls while the non-adiabatic wall was temporarily rendered adiabatic, and of isochoric adiabatic work.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Then the non-adiabatic component is a process of energy transfer through the wall that passes only heat, newly made accessible for the purpose of this transfer, from the surroundings to the body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The change in internal energy to reach the state *Y* from the state *O* is the difference of the two amounts of energy transferred.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In this definition, for the sake of conceptual rigour, the quantity of energy transferred as heat is not specified directly in terms of the non-adiabatic process.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is defined through knowledge of precisely two variables, the change of internal energy and the amount of adiabatic work done, for the combined process of change from the reference state *O* to the arbitrary state *Y*.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is important that this does not explicitly involve the amount of energy transferred in the non-adiabatic component of the combined process.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is assumed here that the amount of energy required to pass from state *O* to state *Y*, the change of internal energy, is known, independently of the combined process, by a determination through a purely adiabatic process, like that for the determination of the internal energy of state *X* above.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The rigour that is prized in this definition is that there is one and only one kind of energy transfer admitted as fundamental: energy transferred as work.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Energy transfer as heat is considered as a derived quantity.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The uniqueness of work in this scheme is considered to guarantee rigor and purity of conception.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The conceptual purity of this definition, based on the concept of energy transferred as work as an ideal notion, relies on the idea that some frictionless and otherwise non-dissipative processes of energy transfer can be realized in physical actuality.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The second law of thermodynamics, on the other hand, assures us that such processes are not found in nature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Before the rigorous mathematical definition of heat based on Carathéodory's 1909 paper, historically, heat, temperature, and thermal equilibrium were presented in thermodynamics textbooks as jointly primitive notions.
[src:heat/heat-p01] That heat is an appropriate and natural primitive for thermodynamics was already accepted by Carnot.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is sometimes proposed that this traditional kind of presentation necessarily rests on "circular reasoning".
[src:heat/heat-p01] This alternative approach to the definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat differs in logical structure from that of Carathéodory, recounted just above.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This alternative approach admits calorimetry as a primary or direct way to measure quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It relies on temperature as one of its primitive concepts, and used in calorimetry.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is presupposed that enough processes exist physically to allow measurement of differences in internal energies.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such processes are not restricted to adiabatic transfers of energy as work.
[src:heat/heat-p01] They include calorimetry, which is the commonest practical way of finding internal energy differences.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The needed temperature can be either empirical or absolute thermodynamic.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In contrast, the Carathéodory way recounted just above does not use calorimetry or temperature in its primary definition of quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The Carathéodory way regards calorimetry only as a secondary or indirect way of measuring quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] As recounted in more detail just above, the Carathéodory way regards quantity of energy transferred as heat in a process as primarily or directly defined as a residual quantity.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is calculated from the difference of the internal energies of the initial and final states of the system, and from the actual work done by the system during the process.
[src:heat/heat-p01] That internal energy difference is supposed to have been measured in advance through processes of purely adiabatic transfer of energy as work, processes that take the system between the initial and final states.
[src:heat/heat-p01] By the Carathéodory way it is presupposed as known from experiment that there actually physically exist enough such adiabatic processes, so that there need be no recourse to calorimetry for measurement of quantity of energy transferred as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This presupposition is essential but is explicitly labeled neither as a law of thermodynamics nor as an axiom of the Carathéodory way.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In fact, the actual physical existence of such adiabatic processes is indeed mostly supposition, and those supposed processes have in most cases not been actually verified empirically to exist.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Over the years, for example in his 1879 thesis, but particularly in 1926, Planck advocated regarding the generation of heat by rubbing as the most specific way to define heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Planck criticised Carathéodory for not attending to this.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Carathéodory was a mathematician who liked to think in terms of adiabatic processes, and perhaps found friction too tricky to think about, while Planck was a physicist.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Maxwell writes that convection as such "is not a purely thermal phenomenon".
[src:heat/heat-p01] In thermodynamics, convection in general is regarded as transport of internal energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] If, however, the convection is enclosed and circulatory, then it may be regarded as an intermediary that transfers energy as heat between source and destination bodies, because it transfers only energy and not matter from the source to the destination body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In accordance with the first law for closed systems, energy transferred solely as heat leaves one body and enters another, changing the internal energies of each.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Transfer, between bodies, of energy as work is a complementary way of changing internal energies.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Though it is not logically rigorous from the viewpoint of strict physical concepts, a common form of words that expresses this is to say that heat and work are interconvertible.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Cyclically operating engines that use only heat and work transfers have two thermal reservoirs, a hot and a cold one.
[src:heat/heat-p01] They may be classified by the range of operating temperatures of the working body, relative to those reservoirs.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In a heat engine, the working body is at all times colder than the hot reservoir and hotter than the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In a sense, it uses heat transfer to produce work.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In a heat pump, the working body, at stages of the cycle, goes both hotter than the hot reservoir, and colder than the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In a sense, it uses work to produce heat transfer.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In classical thermodynamics, a commonly considered model is the heat engine.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It consists of four bodies: the working body, the hot reservoir, the cold reservoir, and the work reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A cyclic process leaves the working body in an unchanged state, and is envisaged as being repeated indefinitely often.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Work transfers between the working body and the work reservoir are envisaged as reversible, and thus only one work reservoir is needed.
[src:heat/heat-p01] But two thermal reservoirs are needed, because transfer of energy as heat is irreversible.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A single cycle sees energy taken by the working body from the hot reservoir and sent to the two other reservoirs, the work reservoir and the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The hot reservoir always and only supplies energy, and the cold reservoir always and only receives energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that no cycle can occur in which no energy is received by the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat engines achieve higher efficiency when the ratio of the initial and final temperature is greater.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Another commonly considered model is the heat pump or refrigerator.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Again there are four bodies: the working body, the hot reservoir, the cold reservoir, and the work reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A single cycle starts with the working body colder than the cold reservoir, and then energy is taken in as heat by the working body from the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Then the work reservoir does work on the working body, adding more to its internal energy, making it hotter than the hot reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The hot working body passes heat to the hot reservoir, but still remains hotter than the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Then, by allowing it to expand without passing heat to another body, the working body is made colder than the cold reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It can now accept heat transfer from the cold reservoir to start another cycle.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The device has transported energy from a colder to a hotter reservoir, but this is not regarded as by an inanimate agency; rather, it is regarded as by the harnessing of work .
[src:heat/heat-p01] This is because work is supplied from the work reservoir, not just by a simple thermodynamic process, but by a cycle of thermodynamic operations and processes, which may be regarded as directed by an animate or harnessing agency.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Accordingly, the cycle is still in accord with the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The 'efficiency' of a heat pump (which exceeds unity) is best when the temperature difference between the hot and cold reservoirs is least.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Functionally, such engines are used in two ways, distinguishing a target reservoir and a resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A heat pump transfers heat to the hot reservoir as the target from the resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A refrigerator transfers heat, from the cold reservoir as the target, to the resource or surrounding reservoir.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The target reservoir may be regarded as leaking: when the target leaks heat to the surroundings, heat pumping is used; when the target leaks coldness to the surroundings, refrigeration is used.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The engines harness work to overcome the leaks.
[src:heat/heat-p01] According to Planck, there are three main conceptual approaches to heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] One is the microscopic or kinetic theory approach.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The other two are macroscopic approaches.
[src:heat/heat-p01] One of the macroscopic approaches is through the law of conservation of energy taken as prior to thermodynamics, with a mechanical analysis of processes, for example in the work of Helmholtz.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This mechanical view is taken in this article as currently customary for thermodynamic theory.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The other macroscopic approach is the thermodynamic one, which admits heat as a primitive concept, which contributes, by scientific induction to knowledge of the law of conservation of energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This view is widely taken as the practical one, quantity of heat being measured by calorimetry.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Bailyn also distinguishes the two macroscopic approaches as the mechanical and the thermodynamic.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The thermodynamic view was taken by the founders of thermodynamics in the nineteenth century.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It regards quantity of energy transferred as heat as a primitive concept coherent with a primitive concept of temperature, measured primarily by calorimetry.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A calorimeter is a body in the surroundings of the system, with its own temperature and internal energy; when it is connected to the system by a path for heat transfer, changes in it measure heat transfer.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The mechanical view was pioneered by Helmholtz and developed and used in the twentieth century, largely through the influence of Max Born.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It regards quantity of heat transferred as heat as a derived concept, defined for closed systems as quantity of heat transferred by mechanisms other than work transfer, the latter being regarded as primitive for thermodynamics, defined by macroscopic mechanics.
[src:heat/heat-p01] According to Born, the transfer of internal energy between open systems that accompanies transfer of matter "cannot be reduced to mechanics".
[src:heat/heat-p01] It follows that there is no well-founded definition of quantities of energy transferred as heat or as work associated with transfer of matter.
[src:heat/heat-p01] If cross-effects that result in diffusive transfer of internal energy were also labeled as heat transfers, they would sometimes violate the rule that pure heat transfer occurs only down a temperature gradient, never up one.
[src:heat/heat-p01] They would also contradict the principle that all heat transfer is of one and the same kind, a principle founded on the idea of heat conduction between closed systems.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In these circumstances, if perchance it happens that no transfer of matter is actualized, and there are no cross-effects, then the thermodynamic concept and the mechanical concept coincide, as if one were dealing with closed systems.
[src:heat/heat-p01] But when there is transfer of matter, the exact laws by which temperature gradient drives diffusive flux of internal energy, rather than being exactly knowable, mostly need to be assumed, and in many cases are practically unverifiable.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Consequently, when there is transfer of matter, the calculation of the pure 'heat flux' component of the diffusive flux of internal energy rests on practically unverifiable assumptions.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This is a reason to think of heat as a specialized concept that relates primarily and precisely to closed systems, and applicable only in a very restricted way to open systems.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In many writings in this context, the term "heat flux" is used when what is meant is therefore more accurately called diffusive flux of internal energy; such usage of the term "heat flux" is a residue of older and now obsolete language usage that allowed that a body may have a "heat content".
[src:heat/heat-p01] In the kinetic theory, heat is explained in terms of the microscopic motions and interactions of constituent particles, such as electrons, atoms, and molecules.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The immediate meaning of the kinetic energy of the constituent particles is not as heat.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is as a component of internal energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In microscopic terms, heat is a transfer quantity, and is described by a transport theory, not as steadily localized kinetic energy of particles.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat transfer arises from temperature gradients or differences, through the diffuse exchange of microscopic kinetic and potential particle energy, by particle collisions and other interactions.
[src:heat/heat-p01] An early and vague expression of this was made by Francis Bacon.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Precise and detailed versions of it were developed in the nineteenth century.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is possible for macroscopic thermodynamic work to alter the occupation numbers without change in the values of the system energy levels themselves, but what distinguishes transfer as heat is that the transfer is entirely due to disordered, microscopic action, including radiative transfer.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A mathematical definition can be formulated for small increments of quasi-static adiabatic work in terms of the statistical distribution of an ensemble of microstates.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Quantity of heat transferred can be measured by calorimetry, or determined through calculations based on other quantities.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Calorimetry is the empirical basis of the idea of quantity of heat transferred in a process.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The transferred heat is measured by changes in a body of known properties, for example, temperature rise, change in volume or length, or phase change, such as melting of ice.
[src:heat/heat-p01] A calculation of quantity of heat transferred can rely on a hypothetical quantity of energy transferred as adiabatic work and on the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such calculation is the primary approach of many theoretical studies of quantity of heat transferred.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The discipline of heat transfer, typically considered an aspect of mechanical engineering and chemical engineering, deals with specific applied methods by which thermal energy in a system is generated, or converted, or transferred to another system.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Although the definition of heat implicitly means the transfer of energy, the term *heat transfer* encompasses this traditional usage in many engineering disciplines and laymen language.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Convection may be described as the combined effects of conduction and fluid flow.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This entire process is often regarded as an additional mechanism of heat transfer, although technically, "heat transfer" and thus heating and cooling occurs only on either end of such a conductive flow, but not as a result of flow.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Thus, conduction can be said to "transfer" heat only as a net result of the process, but may not do so at every time within the complicated convective process.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In an 1847 lecture entitled *On Matter, Living Force, and Heat*, James Prescott Joule characterized the terms latent heat and sensible heat as components of heat each affecting distinct physical phenomena, namely the potential and kinetic energy of particles, respectively.
[src:heat/heat-p01] He described latent energy as the energy possessed via a distancing of particles where attraction was over a greater distance, i.e. a form of potential energy, and the sensible heat as an energy involving the motion of particles, i.e. kinetic energy.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Latent heat is the heat released or absorbed by a chemical substance or a thermodynamic system during a change of state that occurs without a change in temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such a process may be a phase transition, such as the melting of ice or the boiling of water.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat capacity is a measurable physical quantity equal to the ratio of the heat added to an object to the resulting temperature change.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The *molar heat capacity* is the heat capacity per unit amount (SI unit: mole) of a pure substance, and the *specific heat capacity*, often called simply *specific heat*, is the heat capacity per unit mass of a material.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Heat capacity is a physical property of a substance, which means that it depends on the state and properties of the substance under consideration.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The specific heats of monatomic gases, such as helium, are nearly constant with temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Diatomic gases such as hydrogen display some temperature dependence, and triatomic gases (e.g., carbon dioxide) still more.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Before the development of the laws of thermodynamics, heat was measured by changes in the states of the participating bodies.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Some general rules, with important exceptions, can be stated as follows.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In general, most bodies expand on heating.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In this circumstance, heating a body at a constant volume increases the pressure it exerts on its constraining walls, while heating at a constant pressure increases its volume.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Beyond this, most substances have three ordinarily recognized states of matter, solid, liquid, and gas.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Many have further, more finely differentiated, states of matter, such as glass and liquid crystal.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In many cases, at fixed temperature and pressure, a substance can exist in several distinct states of matter in what might be viewed as the same 'body'.
[src:heat/heat-p01] For example, ice may float in a glass of water.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Then the ice and the water are said to constitute two phases within the 'body'.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Definite rules are known, telling how distinct phases may coexist in a 'body'.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Mostly, at a fixed pressure, there is a definite temperature at which heating causes a solid to melt or evaporate, and a definite temperature at which heating causes a liquid to evaporate.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In such cases, cooling has the reverse effects.
[src:heat/heat-p01] All of these, the commonest cases, fit with a rule that heating can be measured by changes of state of a body.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such cases supply what are called *thermometric bodies*, that allow the definition of empirical temperatures.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Before 1848, all temperatures were defined in this way.
[src:heat/heat-p01] There was thus a tight link, apparently logically determined, between heat and temperature, though they were recognized as conceptually thoroughly distinct, especially by Joseph Black in the later eighteenth century.
[src:heat/heat-p01] They break the obviously apparent link between heat and temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] They make it clear that empirical definitions of temperature are contingent on the peculiar properties of particular thermometric substances, and are thus precluded from the title 'absolute'.
[src:heat/heat-p01] For example, water contracts on being heated near 277 K.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It cannot be used as a thermometric substance near that temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Also, over a certain temperature range, ice contracts on heating.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Moreover, many substances can exist in metastable states, such as with negative pressure, that survive only transiently and in very special conditions.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Such facts, sometimes called 'anomalous', are some of the reasons for the thermodynamic definition of absolute temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p01] In the early days of measurement of high temperatures, another factor was important, and used by Josiah Wedgwood in his pyrometer.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The temperature reached in a process was estimated by the shrinkage of a sample of clay.
[src:heat/heat-p01] The higher the temperature, the more the shrinkage.
[src:heat/heat-p01] This was the only available more or less reliable method of measurement of temperatures above 1000 °C (1,832 °F).
[src:heat/heat-p01] The clay does not expand again on cooling.
[src:heat/heat-p01] That is why it could be used for the measurement.
[src:heat/heat-p01] It is not a thermometric material in the usual sense of the word.
[src:heat/heat-p01] Nevertheless, the thermodynamic definition of absolute temperature does make essential use of the concept of heat, with proper circumspection.
[src:heat/heat-p02] The property of hotness is a concern of thermodynamics that should be defined without reference to the concept of heat.
[src:heat/heat-p02] Consideration of hotness leads to the concept of empirical temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p02] All physical systems are capable of heating or cooling others.
[src:heat/heat-p02] With reference to hotness, the comparative terms hotter and colder are defined by the rule that heat flows from the hotter body to the colder.
[src:heat/heat-p02] If a physical system is inhomogeneous or very rapidly or irregularly changing, for example by turbulence, it may be impossible to characterize it by a temperature, but still there can be transfer of energy as heat between it and another system.
[src:heat/heat-p02] If a system has a physical state that is regular enough, and persists long enough to allow it to reach thermal equilibrium with a specified thermometer, then it has a temperature according to that thermometer.
[src:heat/heat-p02] An empirical thermometer registers degree of hotness for such a system.
[src:heat/heat-p02] For example, Truesdell writes about classical thermodynamics: "At each time, the body is assigned a real number called the *temperature*.
[src:heat/heat-p02] Physical systems that are too turbulent to have temperatures may still differ in hotness.
[src:heat/heat-p02] A physical system that passes heat to another physical system is said to be the hotter of the two.
[src:heat/heat-p02] More is required for the system to have a thermodynamic temperature.
[src:heat/heat-p02] Its behavior must be so regular that its empirical temperature is the same for all suitably calibrated and scaled thermometers, and then its hotness is said to lie on the one-dimensional hotness manifold.
[src:heat/heat-p02] This is part of the reason why heat is defined following Carathéodory and Born, solely as occurring other than by work or transfer of matter; temperature is advisedly and deliberately not mentioned in this now widely accepted definition.
[src:heat/heat-p02] This is also the reason that the zeroth law of thermodynamics is stated explicitly.
[src:heat/heat-p02] If three physical systems, *A*, *B*, and *C* are each not in their own states of internal thermodynamic equilibrium, it is possible that, with suitable physical connections being made between them, *A* can heat *B* and *B* can heat *C* and *C* can heat *A*.
[src:heat/heat-p02] In non-equilibrium situations, cycles of flow are possible.
[src:heat/heat-p02] That is to say, the relation 'is not colder than' between general non-equilibrium physical systems is not transitive, whereas, in contrast, the relation 'has no lower a temperature than' between thermodynamic systems in their own states of internal thermodynamic equilibrium is transitive.
[src:heat/heat-p02] It follows from this that the relation 'is in thermal equilibrium with' is transitive, which is one way of stating the zeroth law.
[src:heat/heat-p02] Just as temperature may be undefined for a sufficiently inhomogeneous system, so also may entropy be undefined for a system not in its own state of internal thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:heat/heat-p02] For example, 'the temperature of the Solar System' is not a defined quantity.
[src:heat/heat-p02] Likewise, 'the entropy of the Solar System' is not defined in classical thermodynamics.
